  h1 Join Team Sw&yuml;p
  
  p
    | People like to share content. Sw&yuml;p is a framework for gestural content transfer, regardless of the platform on which implemented.

  h3 The Problem
  p
    | Manufacturers have been creating silos of cooperability, in which devices can transfer content using novel methods like 
    a(href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lye_cvYj8EU&feature=player_embedded") Photo Stream
    |  or 
    a(href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8lQwj5XDzN8&feature=player_embedded") Android Beam
    | , but where outside devices collaborate using archaic methods like email.

    | The siloing that is happening across vendor boundaries will block innovation and competition in the long term. 
  
  h3 The Solution
  p 
    | Sw&yuml;p allows content transfer across any apps running on any device, mediating content-type translation to provide seamless communication with a device-appropriate gesture. Here's 
    a(href="http://www.fastcodesign.com/1669697/it-exists-mit-creates-tech-for-moving-files-across-devices-with-a-swipe") one example
    | .

  h3 What we're doing
  p
    | We&apos;re promoting Sw&yuml;p as the standard for inter-device content transfer, designing new augemented reality techniques for transfering content, building display-free devices for physical-to-digital Sw&yuml;ps, putting interactive digital displays around campus, and implementing a permanent Sw&yuml;p installation at the Media Lab.

  h3 Who we are
  p
    | Graduate student/entreprenuer 
    a(href="http://fluid.media.mit.edu/people/natan/about/natan.html") Natan Linder
    |  and undergrad 
    a(href="http://listprojects.com") Alex List
 
    | , at the 
    a(href="http://fluid.media.mit.edu/people/natan/current/swyp.html") MIT Media Lab
    | .

